        <p>In 1964, Ken Garland published what I consider to be one of the most important historical documents in design: the First Things First manifesto. 50 years later, I took the initiative to renew it &mdash; and to open it up to designers, developers, and multi-disciplinary communicators everywhere to sign.</p>

        <p>The 2014 edition of the manifesto brings questions of ethics in design and technology up to date with contemporary concerns like online privacy and ownership of data, addresses the lack of diversity in the industry, and challenges us to more closely examine the work we choose to put into the world.</p>

        <p>The manifesto has been signed by over 500 individuals to date, and continues to grow.</p>
