        <p>
            <bm>Rugby</bm><br>
            <img src="img/artefacts_rugby_macbook.png" alt="Rugby on a Macbook">
            <i class="fa fa-angle-right"></i><a href="http://colepeters.github.io/rugby">colepeters.github.io/rugby</a><br>
            <i class="fa fa-code"></i><a href="http://github.com/colepeters/rugby_prototype">github.com/colepeters/rugby</a>
        </p>

        <p>Rugby is a tiny web app that converts RGB colour swatches from 8-bit integers to percentage-based values.</p>

        <p>Rugby was built to fulfil a simple need: to convert colour swatches from a designer-friendly notation to a developer-friendly notation. I&rsquo;m used to working with RGB colours in an 8-bit format (where each value for R, G, and B is written as a value between 0 and 255); however, many of the developers I work with prefer Xcode&rsquo;s default of passing colours as percentage-based values. Instead of making the developer change their notation style, I built Rugby to do the pesky maths for me.</p>

        <p>I originally built Rugby as a Rails app in early 2013, but this autumn I decided to re-design and re-develop it from the ground up using JavaScript. Not only did this give me a great excuse to learn some new things (tools like Middleman and Bower, and tons more JS &amp; jQuery than I&rsquo;d ever been comfortable with before), it also gave me a chance to keep some records of my progress and decisions in building the app from day one. You can read these articles on <a href="http://github.com/colepeters/rugby/wiki/_pages">the project&rsquo;s wiki</a> &mdash; I think this is a great way to give other people a sense of the context, challenges and thought processes that went into the app.</p>
    </article>
